(157, 9, 'pg', 'The durian is the fruit of trees of the genus Durio. The fruit is widely known and referred in Southeast Asia as the “King of Fruits”. A durian is distinctive for its large size, unique odor, and a formidable thorn-covered husk.\r\n\r\nThe fruit can grow up to 30 centimeters (12 in) long and 15 centimeters (6 in) in diameter, and typically weighs one to three kilograms. Its shape ranges from oblong to round, the color of its husk green to brown and its flesh pale-yellow to red, depending on species. The hard outer husk is covered with sharp, prickly thorns, while the edible flesh within emits the distinctive odor. The odor of the ripe fruit is very strong and penetrating, even when the husk of the fruit is still intact.\r\n\r\nThe flesh of durian was famously described by the British naturalist, Alfred Russel Wallace. He called it “rich custard highly flavored with almonds”. Durians can be consumed at various stages of ripeness, and are used to flavor a wide variety of edibles, both savory and sweet.\r\n\r\nDurian from different species or clones can have significantly different aromas. For example, red durian has a deep caramel flavor with a turpentine odor, while red-fleshed durian emits a fragrance of roasted almonds. The degree of ripeness has a great effect on the flavor as well.\r\n\r\n<strong>What are the distinctive features of durian?</strong>', '["The size, the odor and the husk","The unforgettable flavor","The degree of ripeness","The prickly thorns","The color"]', 'a', '{"tipe":"pg"}'),
